<L>'Twas dear, dear! what can the matter be?</L>
<L>Och, blood and ouns! what can the matter be?</L>
<L>Och, Grammachree! what can the matter be?</L>
<L>Bother'd from head to the tail!</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>I went to con&s;e&s;s me to father O'Flannagan,</L>
<L>Told him my ca&s;e&mdash;made an end then began again;</L>
<L>Father, &s;ays I, make me my own man again,</L>
<L>If you find out what I ail.</L>
<L>Dear, dear! &s;ays he what can the matter be? &amp;c.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>Soon I &s;ell &s;ick&mdash;I did bellow and cur&s;e again,</L>
<L>Norah took pity to &s;ee me at nur&s;e again;</L>
<L>Gave me a ki&s;s? och, zonnds! that threw me wor&s;e again!</L>
<L>Well &s;he knew what I did ail.</L>
<L>But, dear, dear! &s;ays &s;he what can the matter be? &amp;c.</L>
</LG>
<LG>
<L>'Tis long ago now, &s;ince I left Tipperary&mdash;</L>
<L>How &s;trange, growing older, our natures &s;hould vary!</L>
<L>All &s;ymptoms are gone of my ancient quandary,</L>
<L>I cannot tell now what I ail. Dear, dear! &amp;c.</L>
</LG>
</LG>
</SP>
</DIV3>
<DIV3 N="3">
<HEAD>SCENE&mdash;III.</HEAD>
<STAGE><HI>Another part of the mountain, a cave half covered with bu&s;hes, (lamps up) Enter an old</HI> GOATHERD, <HI>with a wine-kag in his hand, and his &s;on.</HI></STAGE>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Son.</SPEAKER>
<P>See yonder, father, where day-breaks, here's the cave, father hang the wine-kag at the mouth of it, and then away to tend our goats.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Old Goa.</SPEAKER>
<STAGE>(hangs it up)</STAGE>
<P>Poor gentleman! a &s;ip may cheer his heart, 'tis &s;orry lodging to be tenant of th$s cave for a twelve-$$$ $Span$ to providence, and us Goatherds for board,
<PB N="22" REF="22">
that many a civil and well favour'd Cavilier &s;hould come to this pa&s;s.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Son.</SPEAKER>
<P>Civil! an a plague on him, when he met me i'the du&s;k, as he &s;traggled a league from this, he &s;natched a brown l$af from my hand, and gave me a &s;hower of thwacks on the &s;houlder, by way of payment.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Old Goa</SPEAKER>
<P>Alas boy! that was in his mood, his melancholy, that will as thou know'&s;t trouble him &s;ore at times, but it rarely la&s;ts.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Son.</SPEAKER>
<P>Hu&s;h&mdash;I know it will at times trouble others, and the &s;orene&s;s la&s;ts a week after it, what affairs &s;hould call a melancholy gentleman like him to our wild mountain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Old Goa</SPEAKER>
<P>Diego, I do think I have hit on't, I do think 'tis love has put him be&s;ide him&s;elf&mdash;a&s;k thy mother boy, when &s;he cro&s;t me in wooing, how I would &s;ometimes &s;tart &s;tom rea&s;on.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Son.</SPEAKER>
<P>Troth, father, you have that trick &s;till, I fear you have been ill-us'd.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Ool Goa.</SPEAKER>
<P>Out, gracele&s;s&mdash;hu&s;h, do&s;t not hear him &s;tir?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Son.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, then come away and leave thy charity behind you, and he be in his mood now, we might as well meet the devil,&mdash;run old man, or melancholy will cudgel thee away.</P>
<STAGE>Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> OCTAVIAN<HI>&mdash;ru&s;hes from the cave.</HI></STAGE>
<P>I cannot &s;leep, the leaves are newly pull'd, and as my burning body pre&s;&s;es them, their fre&s;hne&s;s mocks my mi&s;ery, that frets me, and then I cou'd out watch the lynx. 'Tis dawn, thou hot and rolling &s;un I ri&s;e before thee, for I have twice thy &s;corching flames within me, and am more re&s;tle&s;s&mdash;now to &s;eek my willow, that droops his mournfull head acro&s;s the brook, he is my cal|ender, I'll &s;core his trunk with one more wretched day of &s;oli|tude&mdash;I &s;hall lo&s;e count el&s;e in my wretchedne&s;s&mdash;and that were pity, oh! Octavian, where are the times thy ardent nature painted? when fortune &s;mill'd upon thy lu&s;ty youth, and all was &s;un&s;hine, where t$y look'd for years, gayly be deck'd with fancy's imagery; when the high blood ran frolic tho' thy veins, and boyhood made thee &s;anguine; let 'em vani&s;h, pro&s;perity's a cheat, di&s;pa$r is hone&s;t and will &s;tick by me &s;teady, I'll hug it, will glut on't! why the grey beard tore her from me, even in $y &s;oul s fo$d dotage. Oh! 'tis pa&s;time now to &s;ee m$n$t$g at each ot$er's hearts, I fear not, for my &s;trings are crack'd aheady&mdash;I will go prowl, but look I meet no father's&mdash;Oh! Willow, oh! Floranthe!</P>
<STAGE>[Exit</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> SADI <HI>and</HI> AGNES.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>A pl$gue on all hor&s;es, mountains, and quagmires, na$, keep a good heart Agnes, of all the roads to chri&s;tianity, this is
<PB N="23" REF="23">
the vile&s;t that ever poor fellow travelled, how fares it Agnes?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Agn.</SPEAKER>
<P>O Sadi, I &s;hall never live thro' the moutain.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, I warrant we'll do well, do not flag Agnes, do not give way thus for my &s;ake, con&s;ider, Agnes, I mu&s;t &s;upport you, and to &s;ee you thus, I can hardly &s;upport my&s;elf, I have had my load of vexation ere now, but this is the fir&s;t time I ever carried double, I cannot tell well how to bear it.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Agn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Good faith, I do my be&s;t Sadi, and I have one comfort left &s;t$ll.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, I warrant, what is't, Agnes.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Agn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Why, you are with me Sadi, and &s;hould fatigue wear me, and I &s;hould die in the&s;e wilds, you wou'd clo$e the eyes of your poor Agnes; and I &s;hould go in peace with one &s;o near me, who has been &s;o faithful to me.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>No, truly Agnes, I could never do thee that office, clo&s;e thy eyes, I &s;hould have &s;o much need to hold the napkin to my own, I could never &s;ee to perform it, what, art not faint Agnes?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Agn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tru&s;t me, very faint Sadi, and &s;ick, &s;ick at heart.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>With fa&s;ting, poor &s;oul&mdash;the&s;e mountains would teaze hunger into a fever, there are eatables perched upon every bu&s;h, but not a mor&s;el that is'nt alive.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Agn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Fainter, and fainter.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>Re&s;t on this clump, Agnes, and I'll &s;ee if any thing may be found near us to comfort you, I'll fight for it thro' thick and thin, oh!&mdash;a cave and a kag hung at the mouth on't, <HI>(takes it down)</HI> Wine, by the Kora, to &s;ee what providence will do for a chri&s;tian, were a Mu&s;&s;ulman fainting to death, now, this is the fir&s;t thing Mahomet would kick out of his way&mdash;drink, drink Agnes, and much good may it do thy little heart. (Kneels and holds the kag to her mouth) how do&s;t now.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Agn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Troth it has cheer'd me, but&mdash;</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>Well.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Agn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Will not you drink too Sadi?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>Now, does con&s;cience make a &s;tir within me, to know whether I am qualified to &s;ip this liquor or not, do&s;t think Agnes, I'm chri&s;tian enough to venture.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Agn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Go to, marry thou need'&s;t it and there is much virtue in good wine.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, and there be virtue in it, (Drinks) by St. Francis, Agnes, thy religion is marvellou&s;ly comfortable, wou'd we were &s;afe &s;ettled in Andalu&s;ia! I &s;hall make as chopping a &s;ubject for a chri&s;tening as ever nur&s;e put into the hands of a friar: can'&s;t journey onward think'&s;t thou Agnes?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Agn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Shall we overtake the lady Zorayda?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<PB N="24" REF="24">
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>Nay, th$t's hopele&s;s, we are bewilder'd here in the $Word$, and mu&s;t give up all thoughts of &s;eeing her, till we reach $Word$.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Agn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Heaven &s;end the dear lady be &s;afe, I would fain then r$&s;t me Sadi, for in truth my legs fa$l me &s;adly.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>And here &s;tands a cave, yawning as it would invite &s;leep i$ Agnes, and I'll keep guard.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Agn.</SPEAKER>
<P>You will not quit me, now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>I would quit life fir&s;t,&mdash;&s;hould any venture to harm thee, t$ey mu&s;t fir&s;t ta&s;te what a M$or's dagger be made of.</P>
<STAGE>(puts her in the cave.)</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> OCTAVIAN.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Octa.</SPEAKER>
<P>How now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>Here's one willing to ta&s;te already&mdash;this now by the $Word$ of his ro$es, mu&s;t be lord of this manor, hold &s;ir, wh$$her would you?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Octa.</SPEAKER>
<P>I wou'd pa&s;s deep in yo$ cave, to hide me from the &s;un, his ri&s;ing beams have tipt the trees with gold, he gladdens man, but I do ba&s;$ in &s;orrow&mdash;give way.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>Mark you, I do re&s;pect &s;orrow too much to do it wilful injary, I am a Moor 'tis true, that is, I am not quite a chri&s;tian, but I never yet &s;aw a man bending und$r misfortune, that I did not think it a plea&s;ure to lighten his load; &s;trive to pa&s;s here, and I mu&s;t add blows to your burthen, and that might haply break your back&mdash;but to &s;$y the truth, I have now a trea&s;ure in this c$ve, which, if I can prevent it, &s;orrow &s;hall never come near.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Octa.</SPEAKER>
<P>Death! mu&s;t I burrow here with brutes and find my haunts broke in upon, my care$ di&s;turb'd by reptiles, I'll da&s;h thy body o'er the rock, and leave thee to the vultures.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>Friend, you'll find me too tough a dinner to be &s;erv'd up to 'em&punc;</P>
<STAGE>(They strugle, Agnes runs between them.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Agn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Oh! good $adi, for my &s;ake,&mdash;gentleman forbear.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Octa.</SPEAKER>
<P>Woman!</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>Aye, and touch her if you dare.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Octa.</SPEAKER>
<P>Not for the worth of worlds! thou lo&s;t her, mark! he who would cut the knot that doth entwine and link together two loving hearts in union, tho' he may have man's form, but at his birth be &s;ure &s;ome devil thru&s;t &s;weet nature's hand a&s;ide, ere &s;he has pour'd her balm within his brea&s;t, to warm his gro&s;s and earthly mould with pity.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>This fellow now is like a great melon, with a rough out&s;ide, and much &s;weetne&s;s within&mdash;it &s;eems as thou wert &s;ent regged amba&s;&s;ador here from &s;ome &s;trange nation, to treat with
<PB N="25" REF="25">
the four &s;ooted citizens of this mountain, and as we're unknown in the&s;e parts, we'll even throw our&s;elves on your protection.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Octa.</SPEAKER>
<P>Some paces hence, there is a Goathe$d's cot, begirt with brake and bu&s;h, and weather proof.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Agn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Let us thither, Sadi.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>Content.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Octa.</SPEAKER>
<P>I'll lead thee to it, for I am high in office in cupid's ca|binet; I bear the torch before the little god, and 'tis my care to &s;hield from peril true loves votaries.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>I knew he was a great man, but never before heard of &s;uch a place of dignity&mdash;along good fellow, and we'll follow you,</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Octa.</SPEAKER>
<P>They &s;hall not part you, for I know what 'tis when worldly knaves &s;tep in with &s;ilver beards to pluck young loving &s;ouls a&s;under.&mdash;Oh, wander boundle&s;s love acro&s;s the wilds, give thy free pa&s;&s;ion &s;cope, and range the wilderne&s;s, crib not thy&s;elf in cities, for 'tis there the thrifty grey philo&s;opher inhabits to check the growing impul&s;e in his child&mdash;Gain is the old man's god, he offers up his i&s;&s;ue to it, and with mercenary wedlock murders his offspring's peace&mdash;they murdered mine, they tore it from my bo&s;om by the roots, and with it plack'd out $ope!&mdash;well, well, no matter&mdash;di&s;pair burns high within me, and its fire &s;erves for heat to keep my clay in motion, follow my foot&s;teps.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Agn.</SPEAKER>
<P>Out, alas! his wits are turn'd, do not venture with him Sadi, he'll do us a mi&s;chief.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>Truly, the tenement of his brain &s;eems out of repair,&mdash;wilt lead us &s;afe now?</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Octa.</SPEAKER>
<P>Be &s;ure on't.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Sadi.</SPEAKER>
<P>Tuck thy&s;elf under my arm Agnes, now out &s;$ymetar, bring us to this &s;ame Goatherds, and thou &s;halt have our be&s;t acknowledgements, but if thou venture&s;t to harm h$r, I'll quickly &s;tir the fire in thy bo&s;om, thou talk$&s;t of&mdash;and this &s;hall &s;erve for a poker.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>Octa.</SPEAKER>
<P>Should the gaunt wolf cro&s;s lovers in their path, I'd rend their rugged jaws, and he &s;hould bay the moon no more with howling.&mdash;Tread the thicket&mdash;follow love's me&s;&s;engor, come, come,</P>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
<STAGE><HI>Enter</HI> GOATHERDS.</STAGE>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>1&s;t. <HI>Goa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>In, brother Goatherds, by the ma&s;s 'tis broad day, and the blazing &s;un cries &s;luggard upon us&mdash;up to the pens, our goats will choak el&s;e, they have $eeded drink an hour ago.</P>
</SP>
<SP>
<SPEAKER>2d. <HI>Goa.</HI></SPEAKER>
<P>Truly, brother Goatherd, &s;o have we, man has a call for refre&s;hment, and 'tis but fit that bea&s;t &s;hould $Word$ betters be &s;erv'd before him, we have walk'd a good half league this morning, let us wet our whi&s;tles, and then we'll think of
<PB N="26" REF="26">
the horns and long beards of our cuckoldy cattle.</P>
<LG>
<HEAD>SONG and CHORUS, GOATHERDS.</HEAD>
<L>BROTHER Goatherd, mark you me?</L>
<L>Pl$dge me when I drink to thee,</L>
<L>Let us drain the skins of wine,</L>
<L>Till our ruby noses shine:</L>
<L>Mountain grapes, and moantain cheer,</L>
<L>Warm the merry mountaineers.</L>
<L>Lets us push the wine about, Till the last, last drop is out;</L>
<L>Then each Spanish man go, And dance the fandango;</L>
<L>When jigging with lasses, How sweet the time passes:</L>
<L>When mountain grapes, and mountain cheer,</L>
<L>Have warm'd the merry mountaineer.</L>
<L>Sluggish Goatherds, haste away!</L>
<L>The drooping cattle mourns your stay,</L>
<L>Labour till the sloping sun,</L>
<L>Tells you that your work is done;</L>
<L>Then your rough bows with chaplets deck,</L>
<L>And trimly dance to the Rebec.</L>
<L>Then each Spani&s;h man go, And move the fandango;</L>
<L>When jigging with lasses, How sweet the time passes.</L>
<L>And work is done, and mountain cheer,</L>
<L>Warms the merry mountaineer.</L>
</LG>
<STAGE>[Exit.</STAGE>
</SP>
</DIV3>
